/* for next-next assignment (1.04)

three states for data structure, chase(player, hiker road(er) or swimmer), next turn(all start at zero, dijkstras to calculate next move, make turn equal next move), 
sequence(the order in which the movement occurs)
every time a character is created, give them a chase, next turn, and sequence to track their movements.
whichever is the greatest next turn gets its value moved then added on, if next turn values are same tiebreaker using sequence.

Discreet event simulation is what this is called.
this allows enemies to dynamically move using the priority queue.

1.04 doesn't have swimmers in it, add them early.

struct character {
    struct PC * P
    struct NPC * N
    char symbol
    int sequence number, next_turn
    int x,y for position
    when making a character, 1 struct is NULL, the other is not.

}

make a comparator for next turn to check which one is larger.

how do the characters move around the map?
- character map
map sized array of struct character pointers (as shown above)
NULL everywhere except where characters appear in the world.
constant time, more space.

struct world {
    struct map [401][401]
    distance maps // only need to be in world space, if pc isn't there no distance map needed
}

struct map {
 terrain t [21][80]
  characters *[21][80]
}


chars are easy to locate, only 1 byte each, no offset

when locating elements, offset is important

char c[100]
c[57] is literally located at the 57th element

for int, 57 would actually be 228, as ints are 4 bytes each

*(c = 57) == c[57]

the first dereference uses the compiler to multiply the size of each element by the index to get the offset.

void *v;

char *c = v;

c + 10 goes 10 bytes (elements) ahead of c.

if c were an int, c + 10 would go 40 bytes ahead (10 * 4)

int *p = c
p = &c[0]

these are equivalent

using & on a pointer is useless in some circumstances, as the & symbol is for finding the address, and there isn't an adress for a pointer (it is the address!)

char m [y][x]

the reason it is y then x, is that we iterate properly by going down through a entire row then iterating the next, it is more performant to do [y][x]. 
Always outermost to innermost.

m[q][p]

really means

m + (q * x) + p

char n[z][y][x]

n[r][q][p]

really means

m + [(r * (x * y)) + (q * x) + p ]
brackets would be multiplied by the size of the element ex: 1 for char, 4 for int etc..

*/